05289nam a22008055i 9780674060982DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979683592  a97806740609827 a10.4159/harvard.97806740609822doi  a(DE-B1597)178230  a(OCoLC)727949876  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKF9756b.G37 2012 7aART0150802bisacsh04a345.730642231 aGarrett, Brandon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConvicting the Innocent :bWhere Criminal Prosecutions Go Wrong /cBrandon Garrett. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b18 graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Introduction -- tChapter 2. Contaminated Confessions -- tChapter 3. Eyewitness Misidentifications -- tChapter 4. Flawed Forensics -- tChapter 5. Trial by Liar -- tChapter 6. Innocence on Trial -- tChapter 7. Judging Innocence -- tChapter 8. Exoneration -- tChapter 9. Reforming the Criminal Justice System -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn January 20, 1984, Earl Washington—defended for all of forty minutes by a lawyer who had never tried a death penalty case—was found guilty of rape and murder in the state of Virginia and sentenced to death. After nine years on death row, DNA testing cast doubt on his conviction and saved his life. However, he spent another eight years in prison before more sophisticated DNA technology proved his innocence and convicted the guilty man.DNA exonerations have shattered confidence in the criminal justice system by exposing how often we have convicted the innocent and let the guilty walk free. In this unsettling in-depth analysis, Brandon Garrett examines what went wrong in the cases of the first 250 wrongfully convicted people to be exonerated by DNA testing.Based on trial transcripts, Garrett’s investigation into the causes of wrongful convictions reveals larger patterns of incompetence, abuse, and error. Evidence corrupted by suggestive eyewitness procedures, coercive interrogations, unsound and unreliable forensics, shoddy investigative practices, cognitive bias, and poor lawyering illustrates the weaknesses built into our current criminal justice system. Garrett proposes practical reforms that rely more on documented, recorded, and audited evidence, and less on fallible human memory. Very few crimes committed in the United States involve biological evidence that can be tested using DNA. How many unjust convictions are there that we will never discover? Convicting the Innocent makes a powerful case for systemic reforms to improve the accuracy of all criminal cases.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEvidence, CriminalzUnited States. 0aJudicial errorzUnited States. 0aPost-conviction remedieszUnited States. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET RECHTSWISSENSCHAFTEN 2011z9783110261264oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406098240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674060982423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674060982.jpg  a978-3-11-026123-3  E-BOOK PACKAGE